    <id>https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfaf031</id>
    <title>Reinvesting or Consuming Dividends: Account Structure Matters</title>
    <updated>2025-08-18T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Jan Müller-Dethard, Niklas Reinhardt, Martin Weber</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;Review of Finance&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;It is a long-standing fact that households mostly consume and rarely reinvest dividends. Among representative brokerage clients of one of Germany’s largest banks, we find the opposite: 80 percent reinvestments and 12 percent consumption. Of these reinvestments, the majority occurs with a delay after dividends are initially parked as brokerage cash. Motivated by this finding, we study payout modalities (deposits into brokerage accounts, checking accounts, or checks) as a novel mechanism that nudges investors toward reinvesting or consuming dividends. Consistent with a transition from checks to brokerage deposits, we find that the dividend consumption rate in the Consumer Expenditure Survey has decreased substantially over time.</content>
